Inheritance — Interview Q&A (Easy → Hard)
Aligned with your Inheritance.py topics: single/multiple/multilevel/hierarchical inheritance, overriding, super(), MRO, diamond problem, isinstance/issubclass, and real-world Employee examples.
________________________________________
Level 1: Easy
Q1. What is inheritance in Python?
A: Inheritance lets a child (derived/subclass) class acquire attributes and methods from a parent (base/superclass). It supports code reuse and hierarchical design.
class Animal:
    def speak(self):
        print("Animal speaks")
class Dog(Animal):
    pass
Dog().speak()   # Animal speaks
________________________________________
Q2. Why is inheritance useful?
A:
•	Code reusability
•	Extensibility (add/override behavior)
•	Models is-a relationships (Dog is an Animal)
•	Easier maintenance of shared logic in one place
________________________________________
Q3. What is the syntax of single inheritance?
A:
class Parent:
    pass
class Child(Parent):
    pass
Child inherits from Parent.
________________________________________
Q4. What types of inheritance does Python support?
A:
1.	Single — one parent
2.	Multiple — many parents
3.	Multilevel — child → parent → grandparent
4.	Hierarchical — many children from one parent
5.	Hybrid — combination of the above
________________________________________
Q5. What is method overriding?
A: Redefining a parent method in the child so the child’s version runs:
class Bird:
    def fly(self):
        print("Bird is flying")
class Sparrow(Bird):
    def fly(self):
        print("Sparrow is flying low")
Sparrow().fly()   # Sparrow is flying low
________________________________________
Q6. What happens if a child does not override a parent method?
A: The parent method is used as-is (inherited):
class Dog(Animal):
    pass
Dog().speak()   # uses Animal.speak()
________________________________________
Q7. What is super()?
A: super() calls a method from the next class in the MRO (usually the parent), without hardcoding the parent name.
class Car(Vehicle):
    def start(self):
        super().start()
        print("Car started")
________________________________________
Q8. Why use super() in __init__?
A: To initialize the parent part of the object correctly:
class Employee:
    def __init__(self, name, salary):
        self.name = name
        self.salary = salary
class Developer(Employee):
    def __init__(self, name, salary, prog_lang):
        super().__init__(name, salary)
        self.prog_lang = prog_lang
________________________________________
Q9. What is multilevel inheritance?
A: A chain: Grandparent → Parent → Child:
class Grandparent: ...
class Parent(Grandparent): ...
class Child(Parent): ...
________________________________________
Q10. What is hierarchical inheritance?
A: Multiple classes inherit from the same parent:
class Shape: ...
class Rectangle(Shape): ...
class Circle(Shape): ...
________________________________________
Q11. What is multiple inheritance?
A: A class inherits from more than one parent:
class Child(Father, Mother):
    pass
________________________________________
Q12. How do you check inheritance relationships?
A:
isinstance(c, Child)      # object is instance of class?
isinstance(c, Father)     # True if Father is parent
issubclass(Child, Father) # Child is subclass of Father?
________________________________________
Q13. Can a child access parent attributes/methods?
A: Yes, public and protected-by-convention members. Direct access to __private parent attributes is blocked by name mangling.
________________________________________
Q14. What is an “is-a” relationship?
A: Inheritance models “is-a”:
•	Developer is an Employee
•	Dog is an Animal
Use inheritance for true is-a design; use composition for “has-a”.
________________________________________
Q15. Give a real-world inheritance example.
A: Employee hierarchy:
class Employee: ...
class Developer(Employee): ...
class Manager(Employee): ...
Shared fields (name, salary) live in Employee; role-specific behavior is overridden in children.
________________________________________
Level 2: Medium
Q16. What is the difference between overriding and overloading?
A:
•	Overriding — child redefines parent method (Python supports this)
•	Overloading — same name, different signatures (Python does not support true overloading; last definition wins)
________________________________________
Q17. How does super() work with method chaining?
A: Each super().method() calls the next class up the MRO:
class Base:
    def greet(self):
        print("Hello from Base")
class Middle(Base):
    def greet(self):
        print("Hello from Middle, before Base")
        super().greet()
        print("Hello from Middle, after Base")
class ChildMost(Middle):
    def greet(self):
        print("Hello from ChildMost, before Middle")
        super().greet()
        print("Hello from ChildMost, after Middle")
Call order: ChildMost → Middle → Base → back down.
________________________________________
Q18. What is MRO (Method Resolution Order)?
A: The order Python searches for methods/attributes in inheritance. View it with:
print(D.mro())
print(D.__mro__)
Python uses C3 linearization.
________________________________________
Q19. What is the diamond problem?
A: When a class inherits from two classes that share a common parent:
    A
   / \
  B   C
   \ /
    D
Python resolves this using MRO so each class appears once in a consistent order.
class D(B, C):
    pass
D().show()   # follows D → B → C → A → object
________________________________________
Q20. What is the output?
class A:
    def show(self):
        print("A")
class B(A):
    def show(self):
        print("B")
class C(A):
    def show(self):
        print("C")
class D(B, C):
    pass
D().show()
A: B — because B comes before C in D’s MRO.
________________________________________
Q21. How do you call a parent method without super()?
A: Call it by class name (less preferred in multiple inheritance):
Father.skills(self)
Parent.feature(self)
super() is safer with MRO.
________________________________________
Q22. What does this do?
super(Child, c).feature()
A: Calls the next method after Child in c’s MRO — here, Parent.feature().
________________________________________
Q23. What is polymorphism via inheritance?
A: Same interface, different behavior by subclass:
shapes = [Rectangle(), Circle()]
for shape in shapes:
    shape.area()   # each calls its own area()
________________________________________
Q24. Can constructors be inherited?
A: Yes. If child defines no __init__, parent’s __init__ is used. If child defines __init__, it should usually call super().__init__(...).
________________________________________
Q25. What error occurs if a required parent method is not implemented?
A: Often NotImplementedError (manual) or TypeError (with ABC):
class Animal:
    def speak(self):
        raise NotImplementedError("Subclasses must implement speak")
class Fish(Animal):
    pass
# Fish().speak()  # NotImplementedError
________________________________________
Q26. How do abstract base classes relate to inheritance?
A: ABCs force subclasses to implement methods:
from abc import ABC, abstractmethod
class Shape(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def area(self):
        pass
You cannot instantiate Shape directly.
________________________________________
Q27. Can a child access __private members of a parent?
A: Not directly. __value in parent becomes _Parent__value. Child cannot use self.__value for parent’s private attribute.
________________________________________
Q28. What is hybrid inheritance?
A: A mix of inheritance types (e.g., multiple + multilevel). Python handles method lookup via MRO.
________________________________________
Q29. Difference between isinstance and issubclass?
A:
•	isinstance(obj, Class) — checks object
•	issubclass(Sub, Super) — checks class relationship
isinstance(dev1, Employee)     # True
issubclass(Developer, Employee) # True
________________________________________
Q30. What is composition vs inheritance?
A:
•	Inheritance: is-a (Car is a Vehicle)
•	Composition: has-a (Manager has a list of Employees)
class Manager(Employee):
    def __init__(self, name, salary, team):
        super().__init__(name, salary)
        self.team = team   # composition
________________________________________
Q31. What happens with conflicting methods in multiple inheritance?
A: The first matching method in MRO wins:
class Child(Father, Mother):
    def skills(self):
        super().skills()   # Father.skills if Father is first
________________________________________
Q32. How do you print MRO for learning?
A:
def print_mro(cls):
    for c in cls.__mro__:
        print(c.__name__)
print_mro(ChildMost)
# ChildMost, Middle, Base, object
________________________________________
Q33. What is cooperative multiple inheritance?
A: Designing methods so every class uses super() and participates correctly in MRO chaining (especially important with diamond hierarchies).
________________________________________
Q34. Common inheritance errors?
A:
1.	Forgetting super().__init__(...)
2.	Wrong argument order in child constructor
3.	Calling nonexistent inherited method → AttributeError
4.	Misunderstanding MRO in multiple inheritance
5.	Overusing inheritance instead of composition
________________________________________
Q35. Employee example: how does inheritance help?
A: Shared logic in Employee.show() / attributes; Developer and Manager override show() for role-specific output while reusing parent initialization via super().
________________________________________
Level 3: Hard
Q36. What is C3 linearization?
A: The algorithm Python uses to compute MRO. It ensures:
•	Children before parents
•	Parent order preserved as declared
•	Each class appears only once
This solves the diamond problem consistently.
________________________________________
Q37. What is the output?
class A:
    def do(self):
        print("A.do()")
class B(A):
    pass
class C(A):
    def do(self):
        print("C.do()")
class D(B, C):
    def do(self):
        super().do()
D().do()
print(D.mro())
A: Prints C.do() because MRO is roughly D → B → C → A → object, and B has no do, so super() from D reaches C.do().
________________________________________
Q38. What is the output?
class Father:
    def skills(self):
        print("Father")
class Mother:
    def skills(self):
        print("Mother")
class Child(Father, Mother):
    def skills(self):
        super().skills()
        print("Child")
Child().skills()
A:
Father
Child
super() follows MRO: Child → Father → Mother → object.
________________________________________
Q39. How does changing parent order change behavior?
class Child(Mother, Father):
    def skills(self):
        super().skills()
A: Now super().skills() calls Mother.skills() first. Parent order in the class definition matters.
________________________________________
Q40. What is the difference between these?
super().start()
Vehicle.start(self)
A:
•	super().start() — MRO-aware; correct for multiple inheritance
•	Vehicle.start(self) — hardcodes parent; can skip siblings in MRO and break cooperative inheritance
________________________________________
Q41. Predict the output:
class Grandparent:
    def feature(self):
        print("Grandparent")
class Parent(Grandparent):
    def feature(self):
        print("Parent")
class Child(Parent):
    def feature(self):
        print("Child")
c = Child()
c.feature()
super(Child, c).feature()
super(Parent, c).feature()
A:
Child
Parent
Grandparent
________________________________________
Q42. What happens if you forget super().__init__?
class Person:
    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name
class Employee(Person):
    def __init__(self, name, emp_id):
        self.emp_id = emp_id
A: Employee(...) won’t set name unless you call super().__init__(name). Accessing emp.name → AttributeError.
________________________________________
Q43. Can __init__ be overridden without calling parent __init__?
A: Yes, but usually wrong if parent sets required state. Always call super().__init__ unless you intentionally replace full initialization.
________________________________________
Q44. What is the output?
class A:
    def __init__(self):
        print("A init")
class B(A):
    def __init__(self):
        print("B init")
        super().__init__()
class C(A):
    def __init__(self):
        print("C init")
        super().__init__()
class D(B, C):
    def __init__(self):
        print("D init")
        super().__init__()
D()
A: Typical cooperative output:
D init
B init
C init
A init
(Exact chain follows MRO: D → B → C → A.)
________________________________________
Q45. Why does Python prefer super() over hardcoding parent class names?
A: Because with multiple inheritance, the “next” class is determined by MRO, not by a single hardcoded parent. super() keeps initialization/method chaining correct.
________________________________________
Q46. What is the output?
print(isinstance(Manager("X", 1, []), Employee))
print(issubclass(Manager, Developer))
print(issubclass(Developer, Employee))
A:
True
False
True
Manager is an Employee, but not a Developer.
________________________________________
Q47. How do you force subclasses to implement a method cleanly?
A: Use ABC:
from abc import ABC, abstractmethod
class Animal(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def speak(self):
        pass
Instantiating a subclass without speak raises TypeError.
________________________________________
Q48. Inheritance vs interface-like design in Python?
A: Python has no formal interfaces like Java. Use:
•	Abstract base classes (abc)
•	Duck typing (“if it has area(), treat it as a shape”)
•	Inheritance when shared implementation exists
________________________________________
Q49. What is mixin inheritance?
A: Small classes that provide extra behavior to be mixed into others via multiple inheritance (e.g., JsonMixin, LogMixin), usually without being used alone.
class LogMixin:
    def log(self, msg):
        print(msg)
class Service(LogMixin):
    pass
________________________________________
Q50. What bug can mutable default args cause in inherited constructors?
A: Same as elsewhere — shared mutable defaults. In inheritance hierarchies this can leak across instances if defaults are class-level or default list/dict args.
Prefer None + create new list inside __init__ (as with team=[] anti-pattern).
________________________________________
Q51. What is the output?
class A:
    x = "A"
class B(A):
    pass
class C(A):
    x = "C"
class D(B, C):
    pass
print(D.x)
print(D.mro())
A: "C" — attribute lookup follows MRO: D → B → C → A; B has no x, so C.x is found.
________________________________________
Q52. How does method lookup work step-by-step for an object?
A:
1.	Instance __dict__
2.	Class of instance
3.	Follow MRO of that class
4.	If not found → AttributeError
Inheritance affects steps 2–3.
________________________________________
Q53. When should you avoid inheritance?
A: When relationship is not truly “is-a”, when hierarchies get deep/fragile, or when you only need reuse of behavior — prefer composition. Example: Library has Books, rather than Library(Book).
________________________________________
Q54. Design question: Manager contains Developers — inheritance or composition?
A: Both:
•	Manager inherits Employee (is-an employee)
•	Manager composes a team list of employees (has-a team)
This is the pattern in your mini-project.
________________________________________
Q55. Explain this interview favorite:
class A: 
    def f(self): print("A")
class B(A):
    def f(self):
        print("B")
        super().f()
class C(A):
    def f(self):
        print("C")
        super().f()
class D(B, C):
    def f(self):
        print("D")
        super().f()
D().f()
A: Output:
D
B
C
A
Because cooperative super() walks MRO: D → B → C → A.
